  "prompt": "Why can't planets be different shapes?",
  "response": "Planets are generally spherical (or more precisely, slightly oblate spheroids) due to gravity. Here's why:\n\n1. Gravitational force: When a planet forms, its own gravity pulls all of its mass toward its center, creating a spherical shape.\n\n2. Hydrostatic equilibrium: Large celestial bodies with enough mass will naturally pull themselves into a nearly round shape as their gravity overcomes the structural strength of the material.\n\n3. Size matters: Smaller objects like asteroids can have irregular shapes because they don't have enough mass to overcome their own structural rigidity.\n\n4. Rotation effects: Planets do have a slight bulge at the equator due to their rotation, making them slightly wider at the equator than at the poles.\n\nThe only way a planet could be significantly non-spherical would be if it was extremely young, recently formed, or experienced a massive collision that dramatically changed its shape. Over time, gravity would pull it back into a roughly spherical form.\n\nThis principle applies to large moons and other large celestial bodies as well, which is why they tend to be round.",
